<main id="main">

  <!-- ===== HERO ===== -->
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="hero__eyebrow">About · The researcher</span>
      <h1 class="hero__title">Aleksandr Okhrimenko.</h1>
      <p class="hero__lead">
        Marketing practitioner, MA student, and the person behind this hub —
        a multichannel research project on digital twins in auto insurance.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== BACKGROUND ===== -->
  <section class="section" aria-labelledby="bg-h">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Background</span>
      <h2 id="bg-h" data-reveal data-delay="1">Who's writing this.</h2>
      <p data-reveal data-delay="2">
        Aleksandr Okhrimenko brings over ten years across performance and
        brand campaigns and is currently completing a Master's in Digital
        Media and Global Communications at the University of Niagara Falls
        Canada. This site is the central artifact (Deliverable&nbsp;5) of the
        capstone <code>DMGC-699</code>, Spring&nbsp;2026, supervised by
        Dr.&nbsp;Wael&nbsp;Brahim.
      </p>
      <p>
        The reason for the topic is plain. <code>Digital twin</code> is
        increasingly mentioned in industry trade press, vendor decks, and
        consultancy reports — but it is rarely defined in a way that lets a
        practitioner act on it. Marketing teams in auto insurance are being
        asked to evaluate vendors without a clear framework. This project
        is one attempt to provide that framework, anchored in primary
        survey evidence and a working prototype.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ===== PROJECT CONTEXT ===== -->
  <section class="section section--alt" aria-labelledby="ctx-h">
    <div class="container container-narrow">
      <span class="eyebrow" data-reveal>Project context</span>
